    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 1,
    "last_activity_date" : 1491996220,
    "creation_date" : 1491996220,
    "answer_id" : 43368188,
    "question_id" : 1565388,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p><strong>Yes. You Can.</strong></p>\n\n<p>You can increase your heap memory to 75% of physical memory (6 GB Heap) or higher.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Since You are using 64bit you can increase your heap size to your desired amount. In Case you are using 32bit it is limited to 4GB.</strong></p>\n\n<pre><code>$ java -Xms512m -Xmx6144m JavaApplication\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>Sets you with initial heap size to 512mb and maximum heapsize to 6GB.</p>\n\n<p>Hope it Helps.. :)</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 1225248,
      "reputation" : 20522,
      "user_id" : 1190934,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 60,
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/Ign26.jpg?s=256",
      "display_name" : "James Oravec",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1190934/james-oravec"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 4,
    "last_activity_date" : 1496117983,
    "last_edit_date" : 1496117983,
    "creation_date" : 1496116437,
    "answer_id" : 44253141,
    "question_id" : 1565388,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>Several people pointed out the specific answers for heap size with the jvm options of <code>-Xms</code> and <code>-Xms</code>. I want to point out that this is not the only type of memory options for the jvm. Specifically if you are get stack over flows, then you'll want to increase the size of the stack by adding an additional option like <code>-Xss8m</code>. </p>\n\n<p>For this problem, the jvm options of something like <code>-Xms2g -Xmx6g -Xss8m</code> would be a solution.</p>\n\n<p>I'm sharing this information as my google searches on how to increase jvm memory took me to this solution, and the solutions didn't work with high amounts of memory allocation. Once I figured out what the specific settings were for, I was able to google how to increase the stack size and found the missing param. :) Hope this saves others time, as it would of saved me a ton of time. :)</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 1575780,
      "reputation" : 11874,
      "user_id" : 1462282,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 100,
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/5wvoe.jpg?s=256",
      "display_name" : "Sahil Chhabra",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1462282/sahil-chhabra"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 21,
    "last_activity_date" : 1511167622,
    "creation_date" : 1511167622,
    "answer_id" : 47388044,
    "question_id" : 1565388,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>You can increase the Heap Size by passing JVM parameters <strong>-Xms</strong> and <strong>-Xmx</strong> like below:</p>\n\n<p>For Jar Files:</p>\n\n<pre><code>java -jar -Xms4096M -Xmx6144M jarFilePath.jar\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>For Java Files:</p>\n\n<pre><code> java -Xms4096M -Xmx6144M ClassName\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>The above parameters increase the <strong>InitialHeapSize (-Xms)</strong> to 4GB (4096 MB) and <strong>MaxHeapSize(-Xmx)</strong> to 6GB (6144 MB). </p>\n\n<p>But, the <strong>Young Generation</strong> Heap Size will remain same and the additional HeapSize will be added to the <strong>Old Generation</strong> Heap Size. To <strong>equalize the size of Young Gen Heap and Old Gen Heap</strong>, use <strong>-XX:NewRatio=1 -XX:-UseAdaptiveSizePolicy</strong> params.</p>\n\n<pre><code>java -jar -Xms4096M -Xmx6144M -XX:NewRatio=1 -XX:-UseAdaptiveSizePolicy pathToJarFile.jar\n</code></pre>\n\n<p><strong>-XX:NewRatio = Old Gen Heap Size : Young Gen HeapSize</strong> (You can play with this ratio to get your desired ratio).</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 3658649,
      "reputation" : 1601,
      "user_id" : 3049036,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 57,
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/lbHwY.jpg?s=256",
      "display_name" : "Suresh",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/3049036/suresh"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 1,
    "last_activity_date" : 1583814803,
    "creation_date" : 1583814803,
    "answer_id" : 60611589,
    "question_id" : 1565388,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>I have problem running the py files in my java code using eclipse/STS, getting PyException due to insufficient jvm heap memory. I have done the changes as mentioned below and I'm able to resolve this issue. Below is my System configuration.</p>\n\n<p><a href=\"https://i.sstatic.net/CGcuS.jpg\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\"><img src=\"https://i.sstatic.net/CGcuS.jpg\" alt=\"enter image description here\"></a></p>\n\n<p>And these are the changes I did in my workspace and voila it runs perfect now.</p>\n\n<p><a href=\"https://i.sstatic.net/1aXXQ.jpg\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\"><img src=\"https://i.sstatic.net/1aXXQ.jpg\" alt=\"enter image description here\"></a>\n<a href=\"https://i.sstatic.net/cgdcF.jpg\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\"><img src=\"https://i.sstatic.net/cgdcF.jpg\" alt=\"enter image description here\"></a></p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 4592324,
      "reputation" : 169,
      "user_id" : 3725297,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 60,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/d27e5aeed83c9bb65c2970917f8a9971?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
      "display_name" : "Jagath01234",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/3725297/jagath01234"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 0,
    "last_activity_date" : 1631086567,
    "creation_date" : 1631086567,
    "answer_id" : 69098813,
    "question_id" : 1565388,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>Here are the steps if someone wants to know how to do this in windows.</p>\n<p><a href=\"https://i.sstatic.net/PGAcs.jpg\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\"><img src=\"https://i.sstatic.net/PGAcs.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></a></p>\n<p><a href=\"https://i.sstatic.net/BqxuH.jpg\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\"><img src=\"https://i.sstatic.net/BqxuH.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></a></p>\n<p><a href=\"https://i.sstatic.net/JOTex.jpg\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\"><img src=\"https://i.sstatic.net/JOTex.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></a></p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 10281983,
      "reputation" : 422,
      "user_id" : 7586739,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/7a73d853335ca43ebbc02702f2734f84?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
      "display_name" : "younes elmorabit",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/7586739/younes-elmorabit"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 4,
    "last_activity_date" : 1710426944,
    "creation_date" : 1710426944,
    "answer_id" : 78161306,
    "question_id" : 1565388,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<blockquote>\n<p>Can I increase the heap memory to 75% of physical memory(6GB Heap).</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I don't know why none of the answers mention this (probably because the question is old), but starting from Java 8, there are three dedicated JVM options to control the heap size as a fraction of the available memory, which are very useful, especially for containerized applications.</p>\n<p>These options are:</p>\n<p><strong>-XX:InitialRAMPercentage=percent</strong></p>\n<p>The InitialRAMPercentage JVM parameter allows us to configure the initial heap size of the Java application. It’s a percentage of the total memory of a physical server or container.</p>\n<p><strong>-XX:MaxRAMPercentage=percent</strong></p>\n<p>The MaxRAMPercentage parameter allows setting the maximum heap size for a JVM running with a large amount of memory (greater than 200 MB).</p>\n<p>This is the option that can be used for the case mentioned in the question:</p>\n<pre><code>-XX:MaxRAMPercentage=75\n</code></pre>\n<p><strong>-XX:MinRAMPercentage=percent</strong></p>\n<p>Unlike its name, allows setting the maximum heap size for a JVM running with a small amount of memory (less than 200MB).</p>\n<p>For more details, check out this article: <a href=\"https://www.baeldung.com/java-jvm-parameters-rampercentage\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">https://www.baeldung.com/java-jvm-parameters-rampercentage</a>.</p>\n"
  } ],
